# -*- mode: org -*-
#+TITLE: bplib: collection, refcount, and copy-semantics bugs
#+DATE: 2026-06-20

* TODO [#A] bplib: collection + refcount bugs  :bplib:memory:cpp:

** Findings — bugs

*** [high] BpList::removeObjectAt reads one past the live data (BpList.cc:279-282)
=while(index<lcount){ elements[index]=elements[index+1]; INC(index); }= reads
=elements[lcount]= when =index==lcount-1=, before =lcount-- =. OOB on a full
backing array. Fix: bound =index < lcount-1=. (Same family as BcList/bjarray/
BoListNoRetain.)

*** [medium] BpArray::insertObjectAt drops the last element and never grows (BpArray.cc:229-247)
It shifts within the existing =lsize= and writes the new object but never
increases =lsize= or resizes, so the previous last element is overwritten/lost
and the retained element at =elements[lsize-1]= is leaked. It only "works"
because =BpDict::setObjectForKey= happens to call =resize(size+1)= first;
called directly it is wrong. Fix: grow by one (resize/shift) and release the
overwritten slot before overwriting.

*** [medium] BpObject::release underflows silently (BpObject.cc:283-287)
=release()= does =fRetainCount--= unconditionally; an over-release drives the
count negative, the ===0= re-add to the delete pool is skipped, and the object
is leaked/lost rather than diagnosed. Add a =<0= check that raises (mirrors the
double-release class of bug).

*** [medium] BpDict::addEntriesFromDictionary signed/unsigned mismatch (BpDict.cc:331-335)
=INT32 i,cnt; cnt=keys->size();= truncates a CARD32 into signed INT32; a size
≥ 2^31 becomes negative and the loop misbehaves. Use CARD32 (as elsewhere).

*** [low] BpDict::removeObjectForKey shrinks twice (BpDict.cc:445-456)
=entries->removeObjectAt(num)= already compacts; the following
=entries->resize(entries->size()-1)= removes/releases one *more* trailing entry.
Drop the redundant resize.

*** [low] BpString unsigned guards / underflow (BpString.cc:202,212,239,267,289-290)
=charAt/setCharAt/_insertStringAt/deleteFromLength/positionFrom= test an unsigned
CARD32 against =<0= / =0<=index= (dead guards); =positionFrom= computes
=max=dlength-substring->dlength= unsigned and over-reads when the substring is
longer. Guard =substring->dlength<=dlength= and drop/repair the dead tests.

*** [low] BpString::printOnLevel malformed field token (BpString.cc:131)
=PRINTONLEVEL(file,level,"\"%s\"",*data,data)= passes =*data= (a char) in the
field-name slot. Harmless but wrong; pass the intended name token.

** Findings — C++ hygiene

*** [low] Rule-of-three violations on memory-owning classes
=BpString= (owns =data=), =BpArray=/=BpList= (own =elements=), =BpDict= (owns
=opaque=), =BpRIB=, and the =BpSetFunctor= hierarchy declare no copy
constructor / copy-assignment. A default copy makes two owners of one buffer →
double-free / double-release. Destructors are virtual (good), so slicing is
mitigated, but copying is not. Fix: declare copy ops (delete them, or implement
deep copy) per class.

** Plan
1. Fix BpList::removeObjectAt bound and BpArray::insertObjectAt growth/leak.
2. Add the release-underflow guard; fix BpDict signedness and double-shrink.
3. Repair BpString unsigned guards / positionFrom underflow.
4. Add == delete= (or deep) copy ctor/assignment to the owning classes.
5. Add ASan tests for insert/remove and a deliberate over-release.
